Introduction and Objective¶

The dataset contains information on temperature rise and a comprehensive array of factors representing emissions stemming from various activities within the agri-food sector. This project aims to explore the connection between these factors and temperature escalation.

In this notebook, I will perform Data Prepration which should give a cleaned data for out next step, which is Data exploration through visualizations. Univariate, Bivariate and Trivariate visualizations using relevant target and descriptive features will be studied.

Dataset Overview¶

The Agrofood_co2_emission dataset includes information on emissions from various agricultural and food-related actions. It covers CO2 emmisions from fires in savannas and forests, leftover plant material after harvesting crops, making fertilizers, and more. Each of these "activities" add to the world's CO2 pollution. Also, it includes data on number of people living in rural and urban areas, which helps understand how society affects these emissions. All these descriptive features would help us understand our target variable, Temperature rise. The data is collected for various countries accross the glode between years 1990 and 2020.

Data Source and Description¶

The Agrofood_co2_emission dataset is from Kaggle (Alessandro, 2024). The dataset holds 31 columns and 6965 rows. The columns are, Area, Year and the following:

  • Savanna fires: Emissions from fires in savanna ecosystems.
  • Forest fires: Emissions from fires in forested areas.
  • Crop Residues: Emissions from burning or decomposing leftover plant material after crop harvesting.
  • Rice Cultivation: Emissions from methane released during rice cultivation.
  • Drained organic soils (CO2): Emissions from carbon dioxide released when draining organic soils.
  • Pesticides Manufacturing: Emissions from the production of pesticides.
  • Food Transport: Emissions from transporting food products.
  • Forestland: Land covered by forests.
  • Net Forest conversion: Change in forest area due to deforestation and afforestation.
  • Food Household Consumption: Emissions from food consumption at the household level.
  • Food Retail: Emissions from the operation of retail establishments selling food.
  • On-farm Electricity Use: Electricity consumption on farms.
  • Food Packaging: Emissions from the production and disposal of food packaging materials.
  • Agrifood Systems Waste Disposal: Emissions from waste disposal in the agrifood system.
  • Food Processing: Emissions from processing food products.
  • Fertilizers Manufacturing: Emissions from the production of fertilizers.
  • IPPU: Emissions from industrial processes and product use.
  • Manure applied to Soils: Emissions from applying animal manure to agricultural soils.
  • Manure left on Pasture: Emissions from animal manure on pasture or grazing land.
  • Manure Management: Emissions from managing and treating animal manure.
  • Fires in organic soils: Emissions from fires in organic soils.
  • Fires in humid tropical forests: Emissions from fires in humid tropical forests.
  • On-farm energy use: Energy consumption on farms.
  • Rural population: Number of people living in rural areas.
  • Urban population: Number of people living in urban areas.
  • Total Population - Male: Total number of male individuals in the population.
  • Total Population - Female: Total number of female individuals in the population.
  • total_emission: Total greenhouse gas emission from various sources.
  • Average Temperature °C: The average increasing of temperature (by year) in degrees Celsius.

Additionally, note:

  • CO2 is recorded in kilotonnes (kt): 1 kt represents 1000 kg of CO2
  • The feature "Average Temperature C°", which can be used as the target for machine learning models, represents the average yearly temperature increase. For example, if it is 0.12, it means that the temperature in that specific location increased by 0.12 degrees Celsius.
  • Forestland is the only feature that exhibits negative emissions due to its role as a carbon sink. Through photosynthesis, forests absorb and store carbon dioxide, effectively removing it from the atmosphere. Sustainable forest management, along with afforestation and reforestation efforts, further contribute to negative emissions by increasing carbon sequestration capacity.

Creating custom columns¶

Grouping 19 activities into 5 activities:

The total CO2 emissions comprises of 19 specific Agri-food activities. It should be noted however that some activities are for similar purposes and perhaps they should be grouped together in order to reach to a more hollistic picture of the situation.

For example,

  • packaging, IPPU, fertilizers manufacturing etc, are activities pertaining to the industrial processes.
  • On the other hand, savanna fires, forest fires, fires in organic soils and fires in humid tropical forests, are deriving from fires emissions.
  • Aditionally, emissions coming from manure and manure processes, along with rice cultivation emissions etc, could also be grouped together as they pertain to cultivation emissions.
  • Agri-food systems waste disposal emissions remains as single activity
  • similarly, Food Household consumption emissions remains a single activity

Grouping variables together on this basis can lead to a clearer understanding of the emissions. Hence, there will be 5 categories: industrial emissions, cultivation emissions, waste disposal emissions, consumption emissions, and fire emissions, as seen bellow.

In [29]:
# Select relevant columns
selected_columns = ['Area', 'total_emission', 'Agrifood Systems Waste Disposal', 'Food Household Consumption',
                    'Forest fires', 'Fires in humid tropical forests', 'Savanna fires',
                    'IPPU', 'Food Processing', 'Food Transport', 'Food Packaging', 'Pesticides Manufacturing',
                    'Fertilizers Manufacturing', 'Food Retail',
                    'Rice Cultivation', 'Manure left on Pasture', 'Drained organic soils (CO2)',
                    'Crop Residues', 'Manure Management', 'Manure applied to Soils', 'Average Temperature °C', 'Year']

# Create a simplified DataFrame with selected columns
simplified_activities = df[selected_columns].copy()

# Calculate the categories total values
emission_sources = ['Forest fires', 'Fires in humid tropical forests', 'Savanna fires',
                    'IPPU', 'Food Processing', 'Food Transport', 'Food Packaging', 'Pesticides Manufacturing',
                    'Fertilizers Manufacturing', 'Food Retail',
                    'Rice Cultivation', 'Manure left on Pasture', 'Drained organic soils (CO2)',
                    'Crop Residues', 'Manure Management', 'Manure applied to Soils']

simplified_activities['total_fire_emissions'] = simplified_activities[emission_sources[:3]].sum(axis=1)
simplified_activities['total_industrial_emissions'] = simplified_activities[emission_sources[3:12]].sum(axis=1)
simplified_activities['total_cultivation_emissions'] = simplified_activities[emission_sources[12:]].sum(axis=1)


# Calculate mean values for all emission sources
simplified_activities_means = simplified_activities[['total_fire_emissions', 'total_industrial_emissions', 'total_cultivation_emissions',
               'Agrifood Systems Waste Disposal', 'Food Household Consumption']].mean()

simplified_activities_means.rename({'total_fire_emissions' : 'mean_fire_emissions', 'total_industrial_emissions' : 'mean_industrial_emissions', 
                       'total_cultivation_emissions' : 'mean_cultivation_emissions', 
                       'Agrifood Systems Waste Disposal' :  'mean Agrifood Systems Waste Disposal', 
                       'Food Household Consumption' : 'mean Food Household Consumption'})


# Sort columns based on mean values in descending order
simplified_activities_means.sort_values(ascending=False, inplace = True)

simplified_activities_cols = simplified_activities_means.index

Grouping countries as regions:

Since there are too many countries, using them in visualizations can get complex and barely readable. Hence, lets group these nations into regions. I'll use a github file for this grouping (Lukes, 2024).

But first, lets fix some issues in the names of the 'Area' (aka, country) feature.

In [31]:

df['Area'].replace({'United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland': 'United Kingdom'}, inplace=True)
df['Area'].replace({'Democratic Republic of the Congo': 'Congo, The Democratic Republic of the'}, inplace=True)
df['Area'].replace({'Bolivia (Plurinational State of)': 'Bolivia, Plurinational State of'}, inplace=True)
df['Area'].replace({'Venezuela (Bolivarian Republic of)': 'Venezuela, Bolivarian Republic of'}, inplace=True)
df['Area'].replace({'United Republic of Tanzania': 'Tanzania, United Republic of'}, inplace=True)
df['Area'].replace({'Iran (Islamic Republic of)': 'Iran, Islamic Republic of'}, inplace=True)
df['Area'].replace({"Democratic People's Republic of Korea": "Korea, Democratic People's Republic of"}, inplace=True)
df['Area'].replace({"Republic of Korea": "Korea, Republic of"}, inplace=True)
In [32]:
# URL of the CSV file which is used to group countries into their respective regions
url = 'https://github.com/lukes/ISO-3166-Countries-with-Regional-Codes/raw/master/all/all.csv'

# Read data from the URL into a DataFrame
regions = pd.read_csv(url)

# Creating a function that takes in the country name and specifies a region for it
def get_region_by_country(country_name):
    # Find the region for the given country name
    try:
        country_region = regions[regions['name'] == country_name]['sub-region'].iloc[0]
        return country_region
    except:
        return None

# Applying the custom function on our Agri-food CO2 emission dataset
df['country_region'] = df['Area'].apply(get_region_by_country)

# Applying the custom function for simplified_activities dataframe as well 
simplified_activities['country_region'] = simplified_activities['Area'].apply(get_region_by_country)

Trivariate Visualisation¶

Total CO2 Emission vs Average Temperature Rise by year:

Recall, the "Total CO2 Emission vs Average Temperature Rise" scatter plot which was cluttered at the 0th point. Lets make that plot readable by getting rid of the cluttering using mean values of the CO2 emissions and Temperature rise grouped over the Years. This should significantly reduce the number of data points, thus uncluttering the 0th point.

In [44]:
from matplotlib.ticker import FuncFormatter # We use this to convert a big number to millions

#Let's group by year and calculate mean annual temperature and total annual emissions for all countries cummulatively.
temp = df.iloc[:,  1:].groupby('Year').agg({'Average Temperature °C':'mean', 'total_emission':'sum'} ) 
                                                                                                       
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (12, 6))
g = sns.scatterplot(data = temp, x = 'total_emission', y = 'Average Temperature °C', ax = ax, hue ='Year', palette = "mako") 

def millions_formatter(x, pos):  # Let's define a function that takes a number divides it by 1000000 and returns it in millions.
    return '{:,.0f}M'.format(x / 1000000) 

# Apply the formatter to the x-axis ticks
ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(FuncFormatter(millions_formatter))

fig.suptitle('Total CO2 Emission vs Average Temperature Rise per year')
ax.set_xlabel('Total annual CO2 emissions in million tons')
ax.set_ylabel('Average Temperature Rise °C')
plt.show()

There seems to be a somewhat linear relationship between these two variables. As CO2 emissions increase, average temperature also increases. Additionally, both the CO2 emissions and the average temperature increase through time.

Key Insights and Conclusion¶

We extract the following key insights from our exploratory data analysis (EDA) and visualizations:

  • There is a linear relationship between the average temperature rise and the total CO2 emission
  • There is a linear relationship between the average temperature rise and urban population
  • Industrial processes emit the most CO2 in the agri-food sector, while fire emissions the least
  • Europe has showcased the highest temperature rise, while southern Asia the lowest
  • Temperature rise seems to be strongly related to Year more than Area/Region

In conclusion, our EDA and visualizations suggest that the target variable, average rise in annual temperature can be well explained by the descriptive features, namely, CO2 emissions all 19 Agri-food activities, Total CO2 emmissions, Urban Population, Year and Region.

Future Directions¶

  • Study the impact of remaining features, namely, negative emissions from Forestland, electricty consumption on farms, energy consumption on farms, etc. on target feature, average temperature rise.
  • Test regression models or explore other relevant modelling techniques.
  • Forecast using the best fitting model (Also impute the missing values using the best fitting model)
